00:01:11.399 --> 00:01:12.440 align:middle line:90%
Has that happened to you?

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:15.140 align:middle line:84%
>>HOWARD BLOOM:
Sounds like wives.

00:01:15.140 --> 00:01:19.640 align:middle line:84%
Or if you're a woman, sounds
like your husband, right?

00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:20.140 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:01:20.140 --> 00:01:22.240 align:middle line:90%
Most people energize me.

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:24.280 align:middle line:10%
But George, you have
to be selective.

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:26.610 align:middle line:10%
You have to hang out with
the people who energize you

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:28.970 align:middle line:10%
and you have to stay
away from the people who

00:01:28.970 --> 00:01:29.930 align:middle line:10%
decrease your energy.

00:01:29.930 --> 00:01:30.460 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Is that what you do?

00:01:30.460 --> 00:01:31.876 align:middle line:10%
>>BLOOM: Well, my
second marriage.

00:01:31.876 --> 00:01:34.250 align:middle line:10%
Look, I thought I was
going to be married once

00:01:34.250 --> 00:01:35.760 align:middle line:10%
and that's it for life.

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:37.710 align:middle line:90%
And I was married for 34 years.

00:01:37.710 --> 00:01:38.650 align:middle line:90%
Not bad, right?

00:01:38.650 --> 00:01:39.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Not bad at all.

00:01:39.090 --> 00:01:39.830 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Not a bad start.

00:01:39.830 --> 00:01:40.880 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's a good run.

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:42.569 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Yeah, but
in 1988, I came down

00:01:42.569 --> 00:01:43.610 align:middle line:90%
with his vicious illness.

00:01:43.610 --> 00:01:45.640 align:middle line:84%
And for five years, I
was too weak to speak.

00:01:45.640 --> 00:01:49.310 align:middle line:84%
And for 15 years, I was too
weak to get out of my bedroom.

00:01:49.310 --> 00:01:51.170 align:middle line:84%
So my wife eventually
got tired of that.

00:01:51.170 --> 00:01:51.950 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It was
too much for her.

00:01:51.950 --> 00:01:54.033 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Yeah, if you look
at the research, people

00:01:54.033 --> 00:01:56.430 align:middle line:84%
who are caregivers lose
five years of their life.

00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:57.800 align:middle line:90%
The stress is much too much.

00:01:57.800 --> 00:01:58.450 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: So you can't blame her.

00:01:58.450 --> 00:02:00.640 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: I can't blame
her at all, not at all.

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:03.230 align:middle line:84%
So she pulled out and she went
back to where she'd come from,

00:02:03.230 --> 00:02:04.830 align:middle line:90%
Kingston, New York.

00:02:04.830 --> 00:02:06.820 align:middle line:84%
I'm from Brooklyn, New
York, where I live.

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:08.840 align:middle line:90%
And I was desperate.

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:12.440 align:middle line:84%
And I shopped for a second
wife online, on the Internet.

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:14.323 align:middle line:84%
And I found one
through Match.com.

00:02:14.323 --> 00:02:14.823 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:02:14.823 --> 00:02:15.864 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Well, you know--

00:02:15.864 --> 00:02:17.130 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: A success story?

00:02:17.130 --> 00:02:17.629 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: No.

00:02:17.629 --> 00:02:19.440 align:middle line:84%
Not by any stretch
of the imagination.

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:21.140 align:middle line:90%
A psychic vampire story.

00:02:21.140 --> 00:02:24.140 align:middle line:84%
So I had heard this
word "screamer."

00:02:24.140 --> 00:02:26.610 align:middle line:84%
But I had never imagined
that a real person like that

00:02:26.610 --> 00:02:28.080 align:middle line:90%
could possibly exist.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.490 align:middle line:84%
And all of a sudden,
I had wife number two.

00:02:30.490 --> 00:02:32.850 align:middle line:84%
And wife number two
screamed about everything.

00:02:32.850 --> 00:02:34.120 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely everything.

00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:35.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But of course,
how would you know that?

00:02:35.580 --> 00:02:36.290 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yes.

00:02:36.290 --> 00:02:38.880 align:middle line:84%
And a person-- some
people are really gifted.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:41.390 align:middle line:84%
When she was looking for
a present for somebody,

00:02:41.390 --> 00:02:44.940 align:middle line:84%
she had this gift for finding
absolutely the sweet spot.

00:02:44.940 --> 00:02:47.815 align:middle line:84%
The strangest gifts, but the
most amazingly on-target gift.

00:02:47.815 --> 00:02:48.930 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: For that person.

00:02:48.930 --> 00:02:49.554 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Right.

00:02:49.554 --> 00:02:52.040 align:middle line:84%
But that same skill
went into finding

00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:56.660 align:middle line:84%
the thing you enjoyed most
in life and destroying it.

00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:59.750 align:middle line:84%
That was her normal
daily course of business.

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:02.210 align:middle line:84%
Now, she didn't regard
herself this way,

00:03:02.210 --> 00:03:04.820 align:middle line:84%
and she wasn't deliberately
doing that to people.

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:08.030 align:middle line:84%
She wasn't using her talents
for evil deliberately.

00:03:08.030 --> 00:03:10.100 align:middle line:84%
But she developed
this, god knows,

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:12.200 align:middle line:84%
as a defense mechanism
when she was a child

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:14.310 align:middle line:84%
to respond to her family
situation or something

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:14.810 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:03:14.810 --> 00:03:16.820 align:middle line:84%
One way or the other,
find the things

00:03:16.820 --> 00:03:19.520 align:middle line:84%
that people love the most,
find it with great talent,

00:03:19.520 --> 00:03:22.130 align:middle line:84%
suck those things out of them
and you can destroy them.

00:03:22.130 --> 00:03:23.845 align:middle line:90%
So there are psychic vampires.

00:03:23.845 --> 00:03:26.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Old guy I
knew in Saint Louis.

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:28.970 align:middle line:84%
We'd go to the Ritz Carlton
and sit there and have a drink

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:29.845 align:middle line:90%
every once in awhile.

00:03:29.845 --> 00:03:32.220 align:middle line:90%
And it was a huge lobby bar.

00:03:32.220 --> 00:03:35.120 align:middle line:84%
And it was full of people
having a great time.

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:38.260 align:middle line:84%
And during the Thanksgiving,
Christmas season, Howard,

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:40.200 align:middle line:90%
it was just fantastic.

00:03:40.200 --> 00:03:42.950 align:middle line:84%
There was always a
guy there named Andy.

00:03:42.950 --> 00:03:47.460 align:middle line:84%
Andy would sit at
the bar and I noticed

00:03:47.460 --> 00:03:49.610 align:middle line:90%
that nobody was around him.

00:03:49.610 --> 00:03:51.390 align:middle line:90%
And it fascinated me.

00:03:51.390 --> 00:03:53.210 align:middle line:90%
He didn't have friends.

00:03:53.210 --> 00:03:56.150 align:middle line:84%
People would kind of
shift away from him.

00:03:56.150 --> 00:03:58.270 align:middle line:84%
And I looked at him
as a science study.

00:03:58.270 --> 00:04:01.330 align:middle line:84%
And I said, Andy, tell me a
little bit about yourself.

00:04:01.330 --> 00:04:04.620 align:middle line:84%
And everything out of his
mouth was a black cloud.

00:04:04.620 --> 00:04:07.660 align:middle line:84%
Oh, I've got two kids, but
you know, they're brats.

00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:09.190 align:middle line:90%
I'm going through a divorce.

00:04:09.190 --> 00:04:10.600 align:middle line:90%
I hate her.

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:12.240 align:middle line:90%
Everything was negative.

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:13.210 align:middle line:90%
Everything.

00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:16.890 align:middle line:84%
I said, every word out of your
mouth when I came here tonight

00:04:16.890 --> 00:04:17.920 align:middle line:90%
was negative.

00:04:17.920 --> 00:04:20.500 align:middle line:84%
There wasn't one
positive thing that

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:23.640 align:middle line:84%
wanted me to stick around
here and listen to you.

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:25.320 align:middle line:90%
You're my experiment.

00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:26.760 align:middle line:90%
That's why I'm here.

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:29.720 align:middle line:90%
I saw him about a month later.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:31.450 align:middle line:84%
There were people
standing around him.

00:04:31.450 --> 00:04:32.404 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Amazing.

00:04:32.404 --> 00:04:33.570 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He's like a magnet.

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:34.380 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah.

00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:36.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And I go up to
him and I said, Andy?

00:04:36.270 --> 00:04:38.570 align:middle line:90%
And he went, thank you.

00:04:38.570 --> 00:04:41.480 align:middle line:90%
And I said, what'd you do?

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:44.885 align:middle line:84%
And he said, everything
I do now is positive.

00:04:44.885 --> 00:04:45.385 align:middle line:90%
Everything.

00:04:45.385 --> 00:04:46.105 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Fantastic.

00:04:46.105 --> 00:04:47.020 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: If it's rainy--

00:04:47.020 --> 00:04:47.600 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Right.

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:49.016 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --I'm
telling people it's

00:04:49.016 --> 00:04:50.780 align:middle line:90%
going to be sunny tomorrow.

00:04:50.780 --> 00:04:53.690 align:middle line:84%
And he worked at it
and he changed it.

00:04:53.690 --> 00:04:55.480 align:middle line:90%
He got a new relationship.

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:58.700 align:middle line:90%
He enjoys his kids.

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:01.610 align:middle line:84%
And it was the most amazing
turnaround I've ever seen.

00:05:01.610 --> 00:05:02.960 align:middle line:90%
I don't see that all the time.

00:05:02.960 --> 00:05:04.060 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Right.

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:07.030 align:middle line:84%
Well, perception has the power
to deprive us of even the best

00:05:07.030 --> 00:05:09.380 align:middle line:84%
things that we've
got, or to give us

00:05:09.380 --> 00:05:11.600 align:middle line:84%
the best things that we've
got from the things that

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:13.130 align:middle line:90%
seem the worst.

00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:15.876 align:middle line:84%
And it's very important
to hold a balance.

00:05:15.876 --> 00:05:17.250 align:middle line:84%
You've got to see
your positives.

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:20.100 align:middle line:84%
America's been seeing
nothing but its negatives

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:21.365 align:middle line:90%
for a very long time.

00:05:21.365 --> 00:05:22.199 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Constantly.

00:05:22.199 --> 00:05:23.615 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Yeah, and
the result is--

00:05:23.615 --> 00:05:25.060 align:middle line:90%
and we don't see our positives.

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:27.690 align:middle line:84%
The result is we're going
to cheat our grandkids out

00:05:27.690 --> 00:05:30.510 align:middle line:84%
of the positives that we
could have given them if only

00:05:30.510 --> 00:05:32.580 align:middle line:84%
we had seen things
in balance, seeing

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:34.410 align:middle line:84%
both the positives
and the negatives.

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:37.450 align:middle line:84%
The negatives are good
when you can use them

00:05:37.450 --> 00:05:39.280 align:middle line:90%
as a corrective mechanism.

00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:41.170 align:middle line:84%
We can use them to
make things better.

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:44.704 align:middle line:84%
But if you don't see the
positives and cherish them,

00:05:44.704 --> 00:05:45.620 align:middle line:90%
you're in big trouble.

00:05:45.620 --> 00:05:46.800 align:middle line:90%
There's a Bloomism.

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:48.820 align:middle line:90%
"Never throw a grace away.

00:05:48.820 --> 00:05:50.430 align:middle line:90%
Never throw a blessing away."

00:05:50.430 --> 00:05:53.000 align:middle line:84%
Now you might find
blessings and grace

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:55.740 align:middle line:84%
odd pieces of terminology
coming from an atheist.

00:05:55.740 --> 00:05:59.480 align:middle line:84%
But the fact is, certain things
land on you as if by accident

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:01.190 align:middle line:84%
and turn out to be
remarkably good.

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:03.450 align:middle line:84%
Even more extraordinary,
certain things

00:06:03.450 --> 00:06:06.180 align:middle line:84%
that land on you
that seem horrible

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:07.774 align:middle line:90%
can be turned into positives.

00:06:07.774 --> 00:06:08.690 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:06:08.690 --> 00:06:12.190 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: And it's our job
to seize the positive.

00:06:12.190 --> 00:06:15.610 align:middle line:84%
Because I have a colleague
named Valarius Geist.

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:19.260 align:middle line:84%
He's one of the leading
researchers of large mammal

00:06:19.260 --> 00:06:19.900 align:middle line:90%
behavior.

00:06:19.900 --> 00:06:23.010 align:middle line:84%
It's a colleague in
evolutionary biology.

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:26.560 align:middle line:84%
And Val says all signals of
any kind between any living

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:30.490 align:middle line:84%
creatures whatsoever come
down to attraction cues

00:06:30.490 --> 00:06:31.760 align:middle line:90%
and repulsion cues.

00:06:31.760 --> 00:06:34.090 align:middle line:84%
Andy was giving
off repulsion cues.

00:06:34.090 --> 00:06:36.260 align:middle line:84%
He needed to see the
positives of those.

00:06:36.260 --> 00:06:38.930 align:middle line:90%
Having kids is a great thing.

00:06:38.930 --> 00:06:40.960 align:middle line:84%
Yes, there are negatives
to having kids.

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:43.690 align:middle line:84%
Squalling in the middle of the
night from an eight-month-old,

00:06:43.690 --> 00:06:44.190 align:middle line:90%
for example.

00:06:44.190 --> 00:06:45.314 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They're expensive.

00:06:45.314 --> 00:06:46.294 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah, right.

00:06:46.294 --> 00:06:47.460 align:middle line:90%
There are lots of negatives.

00:06:47.460 --> 00:06:49.690 align:middle line:90%
But the joy is insane.

00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:53.980 align:middle line:84%
And if you throw that joy out
by refusing to perceive it,

00:06:53.980 --> 00:06:57.330 align:middle line:84%
you've not just denied
yourself something vital,

00:06:57.330 --> 00:06:58.770 align:middle line:90%
think about those kids.

00:06:58.770 --> 00:07:03.230 align:middle line:84%
They depend on the joy that they
see lighting up in your eyes

00:07:03.230 --> 00:07:04.640 align:middle line:90%
when you see them.

00:07:04.640 --> 00:07:06.280 align:middle line:90%
That's what they live on.

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:08.840 align:middle line:84%
That's what gives them their
sense of their own identity

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:10.120 align:middle line:90%
and worth in the world.

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:13.610 align:middle line:84%
So you're not just
wiping out your own joy,

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:15.860 align:middle line:84%
you're wiping out
something they need

00:07:15.860 --> 00:07:17.980 align:middle line:84%
to proceed through the
rest of their lives.

00:07:17.980 --> 00:07:20.230 align:middle line:84%
So it's very important to
seize your joys wherever

00:07:20.230 --> 00:07:22.990 align:middle line:84%
you find them and turn as
many negatives into positives.

00:07:22.990 --> 00:07:25.300 align:middle line:84%
Now you can't
become a Pollyanna.

00:07:25.300 --> 00:07:27.896 align:middle line:84%
You can't fail to
see the negatives.

00:07:27.896 --> 00:07:29.520 align:middle line:84%
Because if you fail
to see them, you're

00:07:29.520 --> 00:07:31.215 align:middle line:84%
going to step into a
pothole and disappear.

00:07:31.215 --> 00:07:32.340 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And hurt yourself.

00:07:32.340 --> 00:07:35.020 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Yeah, or you'll
step in front of a bus.

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:37.986 align:middle line:90%
But it's a matter of balance.

00:07:37.986 --> 00:07:40.535 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You were bedridden
for more than a decade.

00:07:40.535 --> 00:07:41.270 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah.

00:07:41.270 --> 00:07:43.750 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: During this
horrendous time in your life,

00:07:43.750 --> 00:07:46.200 align:middle line:90%
did you stay upbeat?

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:48.330 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: At one point,
I tried to kill myself.

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:51.210 align:middle line:84%
And I was so successful
that I-- almost successful--

00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:54.750 align:middle line:84%
that I was laying like a
corpse on the bed for three

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:55.750 align:middle line:90%
days and three nights.

00:07:55.750 --> 00:07:58.140 align:middle line:84%
When I woke up, I
had stigmata points

00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:00.140 align:middle line:84%
where the blood had
broken through the skin.

00:08:00.140 --> 00:08:03.250 align:middle line:84%
Because the blood weighs a lot
and the skin isn't that strong.

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.034 align:middle line:90%
And it came out here and here.

00:08:05.034 --> 00:08:05.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sheesh.

00:08:05.700 --> 00:08:08.075 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: So I could've applied
for sainthood or something

00:08:08.075 --> 00:08:08.700 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:11.920 align:middle line:84%
And as I said, I lost the use of
three arms in that experience.

00:08:11.920 --> 00:08:14.730 align:middle line:84%
But for the most part,
I wrote three books.

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:17.390 align:middle line:84%
I founded two international
scientific groups.

00:08:17.390 --> 00:08:22.770 align:middle line:84%
And I learned an awful lot, a
tremendous amount about life.

00:08:22.770 --> 00:08:25.850 align:middle line:84%
And I wouldn't toss
that experience away.

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:28.920 align:middle line:84%
I wouldn't choose not to have
that experience for the world.

00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:32.320 align:middle line:84%
One of the things I learned when
I was a kid-- 16 years old--

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:34.980 align:middle line:84%
there were two poems that
meant the world to me.

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:38.500 align:middle line:84%
One was "The Love Song of J.
Alfred Prufrock," by TS Eliot.

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:41.559 align:middle line:84%
And it says, if you have
something heroic to do in life,

00:08:41.559 --> 00:08:44.069 align:middle line:84%
if you have something to do
that you think will define you,

00:08:44.069 --> 00:08:46.480 align:middle line:84%
that you think will
attract women to you,

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:50.130 align:middle line:84%
or whatever it is that you
want in life, do it now.

00:08:50.130 --> 00:08:51.280 align:middle line:90%
Start today.

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:52.670 align:middle line:90%
Start this minute.

00:08:52.670 --> 00:08:54.830 align:middle line:90%
Work, work, work toward it.

00:08:54.830 --> 00:08:56.574 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, you will
wake up one day

00:08:56.574 --> 00:08:58.240 align:middle line:84%
and the life force
you would have needed

00:08:58.240 --> 00:09:00.040 align:middle line:84%
to accomplish that
thing will be gone

00:09:00.040 --> 00:09:02.980 align:middle line:84%
and there is no recovery
past that point.

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:05.290 align:middle line:84%
The second poem was a
poem called "Renascence"

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:07.065 align:middle line:90%
by Edna St. Vincent Millay.

00:09:07.065 --> 00:09:09.190 align:middle line:84%
And it said, if you want
to see the infinite-- it's

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:11.880 align:middle line:84%
back to Michael Jackson, seeing
the infinite in the tiniest

00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:14.730 align:middle line:84%
of things-- if you want to see
the infinite in the tiniest

00:09:14.730 --> 00:09:17.700 align:middle line:84%
of things, open your
heart, open your empathy

00:09:17.700 --> 00:09:20.390 align:middle line:84%
so that you can feel the
feelings of everybody

00:09:20.390 --> 00:09:23.530 align:middle line:84%
on the face of the Earth going
through every kind of extreme.

00:09:23.530 --> 00:09:25.090 align:middle line:84%
She focused on
negative extremes.

00:09:25.090 --> 00:09:28.790 align:middle line:84%
I like to focus on both
negative and positive extremes.

00:09:28.790 --> 00:09:30.110 align:middle line:90%
And she was right.

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:33.950 align:middle line:84%
So what did being in a
bed for 15 years teach me?

00:09:33.950 --> 00:09:36.930 align:middle line:84%
It taught me that
solitary confinement

00:09:36.930 --> 00:09:38.849 align:middle line:84%
is a torture that's
utterly beyond belief.

00:09:38.849 --> 00:09:39.890 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is a torture.

00:09:39.890 --> 00:09:42.430 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Your body and
your mind produce tortures

00:09:42.430 --> 00:09:43.850 align:middle line:84%
that you never
knew could be there

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:45.840 align:middle line:84%
and for which there are no
words in the English language.

00:09:45.840 --> 00:09:47.665 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Were you in
a shell of a body?

00:09:47.665 --> 00:09:50.090 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Well, I
wasn't even in that.

00:09:50.090 --> 00:09:52.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean, could
you even like crawl out

00:09:52.310 --> 00:09:52.580 align:middle line:90%
and go to the bathroom?

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:53.640 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: I could
go to the bathroom.

00:09:53.640 --> 00:09:54.990 align:middle line:90%
That's the most I could do.

00:09:54.990 --> 00:09:57.730 align:middle line:84%
And fortunately, I was able to
do that during the whole time.

00:09:57.730 --> 00:09:58.930 align:middle line:90%
But that was it.

00:09:58.930 --> 00:10:01.120 align:middle line:84%
But the point is
that how would I

00:10:01.120 --> 00:10:04.800 align:middle line:84%
have ever come to experience
that extreme of isolation?

00:10:04.800 --> 00:10:08.890 align:middle line:84%
How would I have ever come to
meet a challenge like not being

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:11.299 align:middle line:84%
able to speak and still
write a book while I

00:10:11.299 --> 00:10:12.215 align:middle line:90%
was too weak to speak?

00:10:12.215 --> 00:10:12.955 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:10:12.955 --> 00:10:15.440 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Without having
been thrown into it.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:17.896 align:middle line:84%
Even losing my first wife,
that was terrible, George.

00:10:17.896 --> 00:10:20.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I do believe when
you and I started doing "Coast

00:10:20.270 --> 00:10:20.590 align:middle line:90%
to Coast"--

00:10:20.590 --> 00:10:21.480 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: I was in bed.

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:21.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You were in bed.

00:10:21.850 --> 00:10:22.300 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: That's right.

00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:22.960 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I remember that.

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:23.630 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah.

00:10:23.630 --> 00:10:27.720 align:middle line:84%
One night when Art Bell
was still doing the show,

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:31.040 align:middle line:84%
one night Art called and I
was in terrible condition.

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:33.480 align:middle line:84%
For one thing, when you have
chronic fatigue syndrome,

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:35.850 align:middle line:84%
the illness I had, your
thermal regulatory system

00:10:35.850 --> 00:10:37.000 align:middle line:90%
goes out of whack.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:37.620 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:39.760 align:middle line:84%
And it means that it
can be 98 degrees out

00:10:39.760 --> 00:10:41.620 align:middle line:90%
and you can be shivering.

00:10:41.620 --> 00:10:43.520 align:middle line:84%
Well, I had a bunch
of air conditioners

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:46.103 align:middle line:84%
on because I had discovered that
unless I kept the temperature

00:10:46.103 --> 00:10:47.600 align:middle line:84%
below 68 degrees,
I couldn't think.

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:48.183 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:10:48.183 --> 00:10:51.550 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: And I was shaking
when I picked up the phone.

00:10:51.550 --> 00:10:52.690 align:middle line:90%
And Art could hear it.

00:10:52.690 --> 00:10:55.932 align:middle line:84%
And Art had booked four
hours with me for that night.

00:10:55.932 --> 00:10:57.390 align:middle line:84%
And Art said, oh
my god, I think we

00:10:57.390 --> 00:10:59.020 align:middle line:84%
made a mistake in
booking you tonight.

00:10:59.020 --> 00:11:01.180 align:middle line:84%
And I said, no,
Art, it'll be OK.

00:11:01.180 --> 00:11:02.670 align:middle line:84%
Well, we did four
hours soaringly.

00:11:02.670 --> 00:11:06.190 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you and Art used to
save my life in those days.

00:11:06.190 --> 00:11:08.690 align:middle line:84%
Because you gave me
an outside world.

00:11:08.690 --> 00:11:10.940 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't have it
except through you.

00:11:10.940 --> 00:11:16.100 align:middle line:84%
So I will forever be grateful
to "Coast to Coast" for that.

00:11:16.100 --> 00:11:20.370 align:middle line:84%
But one way or the
other, research

00:11:20.370 --> 00:11:22.354 align:middle line:84%
demonstrates the people
who value life the most

00:11:22.354 --> 00:11:24.270 align:middle line:84%
and are the happiest are
not the people who've

00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:26.540 align:middle line:84%
had the use of all four
limbs during all their lives

00:11:26.540 --> 00:11:27.960 align:middle line:90%
and perfectly good health.

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:29.480 align:middle line:84%
It's the people
who've lost a limb.

00:11:29.480 --> 00:11:31.650 align:middle line:84%
It's the people who've
lost something profound.

00:11:31.650 --> 00:11:33.990 align:middle line:84%
It's the people who've been
through serious illnesses.

00:11:33.990 --> 00:11:35.776 align:middle line:84%
Because when you
are-- when you go

00:11:35.776 --> 00:11:37.150 align:middle line:84%
through an illness
like that, you

00:11:37.150 --> 00:11:40.890 align:middle line:84%
realize not how little you
have, but how much you have.

00:11:40.890 --> 00:11:41.640 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You have.

00:11:41.640 --> 00:11:42.170 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:11:42.170 --> 00:11:43.445 align:middle line:90%
What got you out of bed?

00:11:43.445 --> 00:11:45.140 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: We don't know.

00:11:45.140 --> 00:11:47.210 align:middle line:84%
We tried years and
years of experiments

00:11:47.210 --> 00:11:48.200 align:middle line:90%
with different drugs.

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:51.034 align:middle line:84%
I take about an hour's
worth of drugs a day.

00:11:51.034 --> 00:11:52.700 align:middle line:84%
It takes an hour just
to take the drugs.

00:11:52.700 --> 00:11:55.760 align:middle line:84%
Of course, I'm listening to
magazine articles and journal

00:11:55.760 --> 00:11:56.950 align:middle line:90%
articles and stuff like.

00:11:56.950 --> 00:11:59.390 align:middle line:84%
It's not wasted time by any
stretch of the imagination.

00:11:59.390 --> 00:12:00.920 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, exactly.

00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:03.820 align:middle line:84%
But I think the big
drug is gabapentin.

00:12:03.820 --> 00:12:07.010 align:middle line:84%
Gabapentin works on--
and this is true for you,

00:12:07.010 --> 00:12:09.110 align:middle line:84%
it's true for me, it's
true for everybody.

00:12:09.110 --> 00:12:11.620 align:middle line:84%
You have a system,
a nervous system,

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:16.430 align:middle line:84%
that works on a balance between
excitement and inhibition.

00:12:16.430 --> 00:12:18.440 align:middle line:90%
The gas and the brakes.

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:21.650 align:middle line:84%
And the gas-- the
excitement-- is glutamate.

00:12:21.650 --> 00:12:26.580 align:middle line:84%
And the brakes-- the
inhibition-- is gaba.

00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:29.310 align:middle line:84%
And gaba-- gabapentin--
works on gaba.

00:12:29.310 --> 00:12:35.770 align:middle line:84%
So presumably, my nervous system
was on over speed all the time,

00:12:35.770 --> 00:12:37.690 align:middle line:84%
and was more than a
system could take.

00:12:37.690 --> 00:12:39.530 align:middle line:84%
And it was burning
out all of my energy.

00:12:39.530 --> 00:12:41.210 align:middle line:84%
So when I got these
two back in balance,

00:12:41.210 --> 00:12:43.159 align:middle line:84%
it's just like
anything else in life.

00:12:43.159 --> 00:12:45.450 align:middle line:84%
It's about the balance between
optimism and negativism.

00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:46.960 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Was it gradual for you?

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:48.530 align:middle line:90%
Or did you just pop out of bed?

00:12:48.530 --> 00:12:51.390 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Took about five years.

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:52.540 align:middle line:90%
It was very, very slow.

00:12:52.540 --> 00:12:55.347 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I remember when you
told me, on the air again,

00:12:55.347 --> 00:12:56.430 align:middle line:90%
you're not in bed anymore.

00:12:56.430 --> 00:12:56.880 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Right.

00:12:56.880 --> 00:12:57.795 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I couldn't believe it.

00:12:57.795 --> 00:12:59.378 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: It was an
amazing experience.

00:12:59.378 --> 00:13:04.290 align:middle line:84%
Because first I got an
invitation to go out-- first,

00:13:04.290 --> 00:13:06.900 align:middle line:84%
I keynoted a thing called the
Global Entertainment and Media

00:13:06.900 --> 00:13:08.450 align:middle line:90%
Summit in New York City.

00:13:08.450 --> 00:13:10.270 align:middle line:10%
And it was an
exhilarating experience,

00:13:10.270 --> 00:13:12.490 align:middle line:10%
because I've spent all
my life in science,

00:13:12.490 --> 00:13:15.520 align:middle line:10%
but only 17 years of my life
in music working with Prince,

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:18.180 align:middle line:10%
Michael Jackson, Bob
Marley, Bette Midler, ACDC,

00:13:18.180 --> 00:13:19.320 align:middle line:10%
all of those people.

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:23.830 align:middle line:84%
So to be welcomed back
into music even briefly

00:13:23.830 --> 00:13:25.510 align:middle line:90%
was a tremendous homecoming.

00:13:25.510 --> 00:13:26.935 align:middle line:84%
And then that
speech went so well

00:13:26.935 --> 00:13:29.350 align:middle line:84%
that they invited me to keynote
the Global Entertainment

00:13:29.350 --> 00:13:31.210 align:middle line:90%
and Media Summit in LA.

00:13:31.210 --> 00:13:32.992 align:middle line:84%
That was taking a
huge risk, George.

00:13:32.992 --> 00:13:34.950 align:middle line:84%
One of the things I'd
learned in this illness--

00:13:34.950 --> 00:13:35.940 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You could
have had a break down.

00:13:35.940 --> 00:13:36.250 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah.

00:13:36.250 --> 00:13:37.644 align:middle line:84%
You overstep the
boundaries and--

00:13:37.644 --> 00:13:39.060 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You've
pushed it too far.

00:13:39.060 --> 00:13:41.960 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Yes, and you are back
in bed unable to speak again.

00:13:41.960 --> 00:13:43.760 align:middle line:84%
But I took a chance
and came out here.

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:46.150 align:middle line:84%
And then they asked me--
International Conference

00:13:46.150 --> 00:13:49.102 align:middle line:84%
of Quantum Physicists asked
me to Moscow to tell-- well,

00:13:49.102 --> 00:13:51.060 align:middle line:84%
they didn't know what I
was going to tell them.

00:13:51.060 --> 00:13:52.870 align:middle line:84%
What I was going
to tell them is why

00:13:52.870 --> 00:13:55.300 align:middle line:84%
everything they know about
quantum physics is wrong.

00:13:55.300 --> 00:13:55.810 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:13:55.810 --> 00:13:56.540 align:middle line:90%
And they sat there.

00:13:56.540 --> 00:13:57.956 align:middle line:84%
George, I was sure
these guys were

00:13:57.956 --> 00:14:00.030 align:middle line:84%
going to throw me out
of their conference.

00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:02.090 align:middle line:84%
I've just undermined
the entire discipline

00:14:02.090 --> 00:14:03.630 align:middle line:84%
in which they've
made their lives.

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:05.940 align:middle line:84%
And they sat there beaming
as if it were my bar mitzvah

00:14:05.940 --> 00:14:07.648 align:middle line:84%
and they were all my
uncles, and I'd just

00:14:07.648 --> 00:14:09.037 align:middle line:90%
done an incredible job.

00:14:09.037 --> 00:14:10.120 align:middle line:90%
I couldn't understand why.

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:12.850 align:middle line:84%
Five years later, I
have a collaborator

00:14:12.850 --> 00:14:15.050 align:middle line:84%
in theoretical physics
at the Keldysh Institute

00:14:15.050 --> 00:14:18.130 align:middle line:84%
of Applied Mathematics of the
Russian Academy of Sciences.

00:14:18.130 --> 00:14:21.130 align:middle line:84%
And he emailed and
said Dr. Rujikof, who

00:14:21.130 --> 00:14:23.510 align:middle line:84%
was running that conference,
has just published a book.

00:14:23.510 --> 00:14:26.110 align:middle line:84%
You have to download it
from arXiv.org immediately.

00:14:26.110 --> 00:14:27.450 align:middle line:90%
So I downloaded it.

00:14:27.450 --> 00:14:29.050 align:middle line:84%
I listened to it on
my Kindle while I

00:14:29.050 --> 00:14:30.730 align:middle line:90%
was walking through the park.

00:14:30.730 --> 00:14:31.840 align:middle line:90%
I got widely excited.

00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:35.440 align:middle line:84%
Every concept I had given
in that presentation

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:37.070 align:middle line:90%
was in this book.

00:14:37.070 --> 00:14:39.160 align:middle line:84%
So I wrote a note to
Dr. Rujikof and I said,

00:14:39.160 --> 00:14:41.170 align:middle line:84%
Dr. Rujikof, I don'
know if you remember me,

00:14:41.170 --> 00:14:43.860 align:middle line:84%
but I'm that crazy American
who spoke at your conference.

00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:46.645 align:middle line:84%
And I got one of those emails
that you get every great once

00:14:46.645 --> 00:14:48.990 align:middle line:84%
in a while that
says, remember you?

00:14:48.990 --> 00:14:50.240 align:middle line:90%
Are you kidding?

00:14:50.240 --> 00:14:52.344 align:middle line:84%
Didn't you read the
first half of this book?

00:14:52.344 --> 00:14:53.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's all about you.

00:14:53.510 --> 00:14:55.910 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah, so.

00:14:55.910 --> 00:14:59.520 align:middle line:84%
And then Seoul,
Korea and Chengdu,

00:14:59.520 --> 00:15:02.210 align:middle line:90%
China and Kuala Lumpur.

00:15:02.210 --> 00:15:04.980 align:middle line:84%
And all of these were
major speaking engagements.

00:15:04.980 --> 00:15:08.920 align:middle line:84%
In fact, Kuala Lumpur had
me design a program called

00:15:08.920 --> 00:15:11.490 align:middle line:84%
"Re-Preceiving Leadership,"
a two-day intensive program

00:15:11.490 --> 00:15:13.320 align:middle line:90%
for CEOs and general managers.

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:15.990 align:middle line:84%
And I gave this really
intensive program

00:15:15.990 --> 00:15:18.440 align:middle line:84%
to these 10 CEOs and
general managers.

00:15:18.440 --> 00:15:20.730 align:middle line:84%
And remember, I'm a
Zionist atheist Jew.

00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:22.030 align:middle line:90%
This is a Muslim Country.

00:15:22.030 --> 00:15:22.613 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right

00:15:22.613 --> 00:15:25.380 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: And we had a ball.

00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:28.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why can't the
planet get along like that?

00:15:28.310 --> 00:15:30.270 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: One of the
greatest things for me

00:15:30.270 --> 00:15:33.860 align:middle line:84%
is the fact that this
sheik who runs Dubai

00:15:33.860 --> 00:15:36.900 align:middle line:84%
and who also doubles as the
prime minister of the United

00:15:36.900 --> 00:15:37.600 align:middle line:90%
Arab Emirates?

