00:16:54.984 --> 00:16:55.900 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: I'm not sure.

00:16:55.900 --> 00:16:58.749 align:middle line:84%
Because war-- let's
take a look at war, OK?

00:16:58.749 --> 00:17:00.540 align:middle line:84%
A lot of people say
war is the results of--

00:17:00.540 --> 00:17:02.373 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And then we'll
get into Ask Howard.

00:17:02.373 --> 00:17:04.710 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: But they say war
is a result of agriculture,

00:17:04.710 --> 00:17:06.619 align:middle line:84%
war is the result
of industrialism,

00:17:06.619 --> 00:17:08.400 align:middle line:84%
war is the result of
modern capitalism.

00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:09.270 align:middle line:90%
Wrong, wrong, wrong.

00:17:09.270 --> 00:17:10.319 align:middle line:90%
How do we know?

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:13.319 align:middle line:84%
Well, our first foremothers,
the very first creatures

00:17:13.319 --> 00:17:17.270 align:middle line:84%
that were in our family
line were bacteria.

00:17:17.270 --> 00:17:19.640 align:middle line:84%
They were the very first
life forms on planet Earth.

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:23.137 align:middle line:84%
Now bacteria live in communities
of seven trillion individuals.

00:17:23.137 --> 00:17:24.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Oh, you're a
Darwinist, aren't you?

00:17:24.970 --> 00:17:27.829 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: But that's more
individuals than all the humans

00:17:27.829 --> 00:17:31.064 align:middle line:84%
who have ever lived in just
one community all living

00:17:31.064 --> 00:17:32.230 align:middle line:90%
with each other at one time.

00:17:32.230 --> 00:17:34.620 align:middle line:84%
And they're constantly
communicating and constantly

00:17:34.620 --> 00:17:36.220 align:middle line:90%
doing research and development.

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:39.580 align:middle line:84%
But if seven different colonies
zero in on the same food

00:17:39.580 --> 00:17:41.620 align:middle line:90%
source, guess what they do?

00:17:41.620 --> 00:17:42.590 align:middle line:90%
They make war.

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:43.770 align:middle line:90%
And guess what they use?

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:45.760 align:middle line:90%
Weapons of mass destruction.

00:17:45.760 --> 00:17:47.190 align:middle line:90%
Chemical weapons.

00:17:47.190 --> 00:17:49.670 align:middle line:84%
We borrowed those
chemical weapons in 1948.

00:17:49.670 --> 00:17:50.930 align:middle line:90%
We called them antibiotics.

00:17:50.930 --> 00:17:53.150 align:middle line:84%
They're so effective
because bacteria

00:17:53.150 --> 00:17:56.042 align:middle line:84%
have evolved these to
wipe out entire colonies.

00:17:56.042 --> 00:17:57.750 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But now what's
happened to them?

00:17:57.750 --> 00:17:59.340 align:middle line:84%
Antibiotics are
going by the wayside.

00:17:59.340 --> 00:18:00.881 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: They're
going by the wayside

00:18:00.881 --> 00:18:03.280 align:middle line:84%
because these creatures
are so good at research

00:18:03.280 --> 00:18:03.980 align:middle line:90%
and development.

00:18:03.980 --> 00:18:08.242 align:middle line:84%
So war has been around
for 3.85 billion years.

00:18:08.242 --> 00:18:09.200 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I would agree.

00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:10.225 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: And it isn't
just the leaders.

00:18:10.225 --> 00:18:11.433 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's inherent in us.

00:18:11.433 --> 00:18:12.040 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Yeah.

00:18:12.040 --> 00:18:16.000 align:middle line:84%
What we have done is increased
peace by a factor of nine.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:19.720 align:middle line:84%
We're nine times as
peaceful as we were in 1650.

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:22.980 align:middle line:84%
We're nine times as peaceful
as those wonderful indigenous

00:18:22.980 --> 00:18:25.800 align:middle line:84%
tribes you hear about who
live in harmony with nature

00:18:25.800 --> 00:18:27.180 align:middle line:90%
at peace with each other.

00:18:27.180 --> 00:18:29.410 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, if you lived in
one of those tribes,

00:18:29.410 --> 00:18:31.880 align:middle line:84%
or I lived in one of those
tribes, the two of us

00:18:31.880 --> 00:18:34.680 align:middle line:84%
would have had nine times the
chance of dying a violent death

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:35.850 align:middle line:84%
at the hands of a
fellow human being.

00:18:35.850 --> 00:18:37.220 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It would have
eaten us or something.

00:18:37.220 --> 00:18:38.540 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Than we have today.

00:18:38.540 --> 00:18:41.340 align:middle line:84%
So we've accomplished
astonishing things.

00:18:41.340 --> 00:18:44.610 align:middle line:84%
The Population Bomb has been
this great positive phenomenon.

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:46.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We have
a long way to go.

00:18:46.520 --> 00:18:48.810 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at some
of these pictures.

00:18:48.810 --> 00:18:53.240 align:middle line:84%
The first one I want
to show you is what?

00:18:53.240 --> 00:18:56.730 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: That's NC Wyeth, an
early 20th century painter.

00:18:56.730 --> 00:19:01.930 align:middle line:84%
And I love this painting because
we talked in the first episode

00:19:01.930 --> 00:19:04.522 align:middle line:84%
that we did about how
it is crucial for people

00:19:04.522 --> 00:19:06.230 align:middle line:84%
to believe that they're
part of something

00:19:06.230 --> 00:19:07.750 align:middle line:90%
bigger than themselves.

00:19:07.750 --> 00:19:09.584 align:middle line:84%
And there is something
bigger than yourself.

00:19:09.584 --> 00:19:11.833 align:middle line:84%
It's called in my first book,
"The Lucifer Principle,"

00:19:11.833 --> 00:19:12.760 align:middle line:90%
the super organism.

00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:14.300 align:middle line:90%
You and I are like cells.

00:19:14.300 --> 00:19:16.160 align:middle line:90%
Your body is 100 trillion cells.

00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:17.640 align:middle line:90%
Mine is 100 trillion cells.

00:19:17.640 --> 00:19:20.430 align:middle line:84%
They're all working together
to produce something bigger

00:19:20.430 --> 00:19:22.750 align:middle line:84%
called George Noory
or Howard Bloom.

00:19:22.750 --> 00:19:25.330 align:middle line:84%
We individuals, as
parts of a society,

00:19:25.330 --> 00:19:26.590 align:middle line:90%
function like those cells.

00:19:26.590 --> 00:19:29.720 align:middle line:84%
And that bigger something that
comes from us is the nation,

00:19:29.720 --> 00:19:30.780 align:middle line:90%
it's our ideals.

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:32.870 align:middle line:84%
It's our sense of
transcendent truths.

00:19:32.870 --> 00:19:34.960 align:middle line:84%
And that's what this picture
tends to-- oh my god,

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:36.840 align:middle line:84%
that's what this picture
tends to represent.

00:19:36.840 --> 00:19:41.110 align:middle line:90%
This one is the big bagel.

00:19:41.110 --> 00:19:43.960 align:middle line:84%
In 1959, I was working at
the world's largest cancer

00:19:43.960 --> 00:19:44.960 align:middle line:90%
research facility.

00:19:44.960 --> 00:19:46.430 align:middle line:90%
I was 16 years old.

00:19:46.430 --> 00:19:50.860 align:middle line:84%
Now I had built my first Boolean
algebra machine when I was 12.

00:19:50.860 --> 00:19:53.060 align:middle line:84%
I had co-designed
a computer that

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:55.300 align:middle line:84%
won science fair
awards when I was 12.

00:19:55.300 --> 00:19:57.330 align:middle line:84%
And I'd had a long
conversation--

00:19:57.330 --> 00:19:59.487 align:middle line:84%
I'd been dragged into
my local university--

00:19:59.487 --> 00:20:01.986 align:middle line:84%
the University of Buffalo-- for
a conversation with the head

00:20:01.986 --> 00:20:04.640 align:middle line:84%
of the graduate physics
department when I was 12.

00:20:04.640 --> 00:20:07.442 align:middle line:84%
It turned out to be a debate
on big bang versus steady state

00:20:07.442 --> 00:20:08.400 align:middle line:90%
theory of the universe.

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:11.012 align:middle line:90%
The hottest topic of the time.

00:20:11.012 --> 00:20:13.470 align:middle line:84%
Four years later, when I was
working at the world's largest

00:20:13.470 --> 00:20:16.030 align:middle line:84%
cancer research lab
in Buffalo, New York,

00:20:16.030 --> 00:20:18.820 align:middle line:84%
the big problem in theoretical
physics and cosmology

00:20:18.820 --> 00:20:23.290 align:middle line:84%
was, if matter and anti-matter
are created in equal amounts

00:20:23.290 --> 00:20:27.035 align:middle line:84%
at the same time, where'd
all the anti-matter go?

00:20:27.035 --> 00:20:28.096 align:middle line:90%
Well, that's a good one.

00:20:28.096 --> 00:20:28.970 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Where is it?

00:20:28.970 --> 00:20:31.303 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: It took me two and
1/2 months to figure it out.

00:20:31.303 --> 00:20:32.900 align:middle line:90%
And it's the big bagel.

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:35.470 align:middle line:84%
If you imagine a bagel with
an infinitesimally tiny

00:20:35.470 --> 00:20:38.360 align:middle line:84%
little hole and out of
the top of that hole--

00:20:38.360 --> 00:20:39.500 align:middle line:90%
that hole is the Big Bang.

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:42.920 align:middle line:84%
And out of the top of that
hole comes the positive matter,

00:20:42.920 --> 00:20:44.250 align:middle line:90%
the positive universe.

00:20:44.250 --> 00:20:47.820 align:middle line:84%
Out of the bottom of that
bagel comes the anti-matter.

00:20:47.820 --> 00:20:49.070 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And it keeps flowing.

00:20:49.070 --> 00:20:51.060 align:middle line:84%
>>BLOOM: Yes, and
they meet each other

00:20:51.060 --> 00:20:52.890 align:middle line:84%
at the very edge and
annihilate, and they

00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:55.380 align:middle line:84%
become the next
center of the bagel.

00:20:55.380 --> 00:20:56.464 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Ask Howard it is.

00:20:56.464 --> 00:20:58.046 align:middle line:84%
You wanted to do a
little Ask Howard--

00:20:58.046 --> 00:20:58.860 align:middle line:90%
>>BLOOM: Oh, yes.

00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:00.342 align:middle line:90%
